The paper deals with decision making in complex environments, which is a key challenge in artificial intelligence (AI). It specifically focuses on multiagent environments, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.MA (multiagent systems) sub-category. The paper also mentions a body of work in AI that has tried to mitigate the complexity of multiagent environments, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.AI (artificial intelligence) sub-category. The paper also mentions the computation intractability of principled solution methods, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.GT (game theory) sub-category. The paper also mentions the formalization of influence-based abstraction, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.LG (machine learning) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with partially observable stochastic games, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.SY (systems and control) sub-category.
